<font color="#FF0000">IT AIN'T SO SIMPLE</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27 19:48:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br>
     Of those who called me a baby killer, and of those who called other vets, I 've discussed the issue with, the same; none were consciencious objectors.  Protesters, yes, but no C.O.s.  Again, why is the term consciencous objector a red flag for you?<br><br>
     As for the many silent vets, the ones I've gotten to talk a little have a variety of reasons:<br>
      1. seen to much horror they were unprepared for or       able to stand.<br><br>
      2. took part in things they would rather forget, and I       don't necessarily mean atrocities either.  <br><br>
      3. survivor's guilt.<br><br>
      4. were blown off or called down upon returning at the       local Legion or VFW post.<br><br>
      5. lost their girlfriend or wife while overseas (this       war had highest per capita Dear John letters.<br>
One teacher at my son's high school keeps very quiet about being a Vet.  Seems he was a bit of a hellion in Vietnam.  He will only say that &quot;it's a part of my life that is over, and I'm a different person now&quot;.<br><br>
     If you want some fire breathing leftists to sink your teeth into; suggest that you find the Winkler brothers who unloaded straight SDS style stuff on the Vets-nonVets dialogue thread back in February.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professsor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


